personal_takeaways: You are a 56-year-old woman experiencing worsening chest pain, including at rest, which strongly suggests a serious heart condition called unstable angina.
Your heart issues are likely linked to several risk factors, including high blood pressure, a family history of early heart artery disease, and early menopause due to previous surgery.
You have also been experiencing difficulty breathing, which might be related to your heart not pumping as effectively, possibly indicating early heart failure.
The newly identified high blood pressure along with an unusual sound heard in your belly could mean that the arteries supplying your kidneys are narrowed, which can cause high blood pressure.
An additional heart sound (murmur) was heard, which may indicate a problem with one of your heart valves, specifically the aortic valve, needing further evaluation.
Other findings include upper belly discomfort (which may be related to your past stomach ulcer disease) and fluid-filled sacs in your breasts, which are common.
You have a known allergy to penicillin.

The plan for your care includes close monitoring of your heart, starting medications like aspirin to prevent blood clots and nitrates to help with chest pain, and diuretics (water pills) to help with breathing and blood pressure.
You will need to have your cholesterol checked, and important lifestyle changes like regular exercise and a low-fat diet are recommended to improve your heart health and manage your weight.
A procedure called a cardiac catheterization is planned to get a clearer picture of your heart's blood vessels and any blockages.
Further blood tests and an initial heart tracing (EKG) will be done to check your kidney function and overall health.

1. Report Increased Chest Pain: Immediately tell your doctor or seek emergency care if your chest pain increases, especially if it happens when you are resting. This helps your medical team know if your heart problem is getting worse.
10. Take Diuretics (Water Pills): Take your diuretic medicine (water pills) exactly as your doctor tells you. This medicine helps your body get rid of extra water and salt, which can ease breathing and lower blood pressure.
11. Attend Lab Work Appointments: Go to all scheduled appointments for blood and urine tests, including those for kidney function and blood minerals. These tests help your doctor monitor your overall health and how your treatments are working.
12. Attend Baseline EKG: Go to your appointment for an initial heart tracing test (EKG). This test records your heart's electrical activity and helps your doctor understand its rhythm and health.
2. Take Prescribed Aspirin: Take your aspirin medicine exactly as your doctor tells you. This medicine helps prevent blood clots and can reduce the risk of a heart attack.
3. Take Nitrates for Pain Relief: Take your nitrate medicine as directed by your doctor when you have chest pain. This medicine helps open up your blood vessels to relieve pain and can help lower your blood pressure.
4. Take Strong Pain Medicine (If Needed): If your chest pain is severe and doesn't get better with nitrates, take the stronger pain medicine (like morphine) your doctor prescribed. This is for intense pain relief when other medicines aren't enough.
5. Start Regular Exercise: Begin and maintain a regular exercise program as recommended by your doctor or physical therapist. Exercise helps improve your heart health, manage weight, and overall well-being.
6. Follow a Weight Loss Plan: Follow the weight loss plan suggested by your doctor or a nutritionist. Losing weight can greatly improve your heart health and lower your blood pressure.
7. Eat a Low-Fat Diet: Choose foods that are low in fat. Your doctor or a dietitian can provide specific guidance. A low-fat diet helps manage your cholesterol and supports heart health.
8. Take Cholesterol-Lowering Medicine (I: If your doctor prescribes medicine to lower your cholesterol (like statins), take it every day as directed. This medicine helps reduce fatty substances in your blood that can block arteries.
9. Attend Cardiac Catheterization: Go to your scheduled cardiac catheterization appointment. This procedure helps doctors get a clear look at your heart's blood vessels and blockages.
